{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Espen Aalberg | image = | caption = | image_size = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Trondheim]] | death_date = | death_place = | origin = [[Norway]] | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | instrument = Drums, percussion | genre = [[Jazz]] | occupation = Musician, composer | years_active = | label = | associated_acts = | website = {{URL|jazzfest.no/event/jamsession-espen-aalberg}} }}
'''Espen Aalberg''' is a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] jazz musician (drums) known for his contributions in several orchestras like [[The Core (band)|The Core]], [[Shagma (band)|Shagma]], [[Kwaz]], [[Håvard Lund|Håvard Lund Quartet]] and musicians like [[Jonas Kullhammar]], [[Håvard Wiik]] and [[Torbjörn Zetterberg Hot Five|Torbjörn Zetterberg]]. He also contributes on a series of recordings.<ref name=discogs>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/Espen+Aalberg |title=Espen Aalberg Discography |accessdate=2013-06-15 |publisher=Discogs.com}}</ref>
==Career== Aalberg played percussion in [[Namsos]] percussion ensemble (1988–1994) and became champion in ensemble playing, after which he studied at the "Musikkonservatoriet" in [[Tromsø]] and the Jazz Program at ''[[Norges Teknisk-Naturvitenskapelige Universitet|Trondheim Musikkonservatorium]]'' (1998–2000).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntnu.no/jazzlinja25/studentene.htm |title=Jazzlinja |accessdate=2013-06-15 |publisher=NTNU.no |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053706/http://www.ntnu.no/jazzlinja25/studentene.htm |archivedate=21 September 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> (1999–2002). While studying jazz in Trondheim, he formed the innovative band [[The Core]] together with fellow students (including [[Kjetil Møster]], [[Erlend Slettevoll]] and [[Steinar Raknes]]). He also established the jazz band [[Shagma (jazz band)|Shagma]] in 2004, comprising additional [[Jørgen Mathisen]] and Raknes. At the [[Nattjazz]] jazz festival in Bergen 2006 he led the band [[Kwaz]] comprising [[Jonas Kullhammar]], [[Håvard Wiik]] and [[Torbjörn Zetterberg Hot Five|Torbjörn Zetterberg]]. In addition Aalberg has contributed within [[Håvard Lund|Håvard Lund Quartet]].
In 2006 Aalberg and The Core, now as The Indian Core, contributed on The Oslo World Music Festival, after returning from a Tour to India with three hot Indian musicians. The result of this cooperation is manifested on the album ''The Indian Core'' (2007).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ballade.no/nmi.nsf/doc/art2006052309323746124971 |title=The Indian Core – Grooven av norsk jazz og indisk tabla |date=2006-05-23 |accessdate=2013-06-15 |publisher=Discogs.com}}</ref>
Aalberg also acts as a drummer in classical music within among others [[Trondheim Symphony Orchestra]], [[Trondheim Sinfonietta]] and "Luftforsvarets Musikkorps".
==Discography== *2004: ''Vision'' (Jazzaway), within [[The Core (band)|The Core]] *2005: ''Music'' (Jazzaway), within [[Shagma (band)|Shagma]] *2006: ''Blue Sky'' (Jazzaway), within The Core *2007: ''The Indian Core'' (Grappa), within [[The Core (band)|The Indian Core]] including Prasenjit Mitra, Kanchman Babbar & Fateh Ali *2007: ''Office essentials'' (Jazzland), within The Core *2007: ''Meditations on Coltrane'' (Grappa), within The Core & [[Bergen Big Band]] *2008: ''Golonka Love'' (Moserobie), within The Core *2008: ''Så rart'' (Øra), within [[Trondheim Sinfonietta]] *2009: ''The art of no return'', Vol. 1 (Moserobie), within The Core & More *2010: ''Party'' (Moserobie), with among others [[Jonas Kullhammar]] & [[Kjetil Møster]] (recorded, mixed & producer by Aalberg)<ref name=discogs/> *2012: ''Basement Sessions'', Vol. 1 (Clean Feed), with Jonas Kullhammar & [[Torbjörn Zetterberg Hot Five|Torbjörn Zetterberg]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=8726519 |title=Espen Aalberg / Jonas Kullhammar / Torbjorn Zetterberg – Basement Sessions, Vol. 1 CD |accessdate=2013-06-15 |publisher=CDuniverse.com}}</ref>
